{"title_page": "H-point", "text_new": "[[Image:H-Point (rev).PNG|280px|right]]  \nThe '''H-point''' (or '''hip-point''') is the theoretical, relative location of an occupant's [[Hip (anatomy)|hip]]: specifically the pivot point between the torso and upper leg portions of the body &mdash; as used in vehicle design, [[automotive design]] and vehicle regulation as well as other disciplines including chair and furniture design.  \n\nIn vehicle design, the H-point is also measured ''relative'' to other features, e.g. h-point to vehicle floor ('''H30''')<ref name=\"ref3\">{{cite web\n  | title = 2004 Mitsubishi Outlander New Car Test Drive  | publisher = Car.com, Larry Edsall \n  | url = http://www.car.com/content/Research/Reviews/index.cfm/action/DisplayPro/aid/138805/Make_vch/Mitsubishi/Model_vch/Outlander/Year_si/2004}}</ref> or h-point to pavement ('''H5''').  In other words, a vehicle said to have a \"high H-point\" may have an H-point that is \"high\" ''relative'' to the vehicle floor, the road surface, or both.\n\nTechnically, the H-point measurement uses the hip joint of a 50th [[percentile]] male occupant, viewed laterally,<ref name=\"fed reg\">{{cite web\n  | title = Dept of Transportation NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards\n  | publisher = Federal Register  May 4, 07 p.25485\n  | url = http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/2007/pdf/07-2011.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> and is highly relevant to national and international vehicle design standards such as [[Vehicle regulation|global technical regulations (GTR)]].  For example, a vehicle design standard known as the [[Society of Automotive Engineers|Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE)]] '''J1100 Interior Measurement Index''' sets parameters for such measurements as '''H30''' (H-point to vehicle floor); '''H5''' (H-point to pavement surface), '''H61''' (H-point to interior ceiling) and '''H25''' (H-point to window sill).<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Riding High: Auto Makers Jack Up the Car Seat; Finding Your Ideal 'H-Point'\n |publisher    = The Wall Street Journal\n |author       = Michelle Higgins\n |date         = December 2, 2004\n |url          = https://www.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB110194232087888545.html\n |access-date  = March 13, 2017\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080502202118/http://online.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB110194232087888545.html\n |archive-date = May 2, 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref> \n\nAs with the location of other automotive design \"hard points,\" the H-point has major ramifications in the overall vehicle design, including roof height, aerodynamics, visibility (both within the vehicle and from the vehicle into traffic), seating comfort,<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web\n  | title = 2005 Ford Freestyle Design\n  | publisher = Myfordfreestyle.com\n  | url = http://www.myfordfreestyle.com/specs/2005_freestyle_design.php}}</ref> driver fatigue, ease of entry and exit,<ref name=\"ref1\"/> interior packaging, [[Automobile safety|safety]], restraint and airbag design and collision performance.  As an example, higher H-points can provide more legroom, both in the front and back seats.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\nBy the early 2000s there had been a global trend toward higher H-points ''relative'' to the road surface and the vehicle's interior floor.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web\n  | title = Frankfurt Motor Show: Will getting more into less become more out of less?\n  | publisher = Automotive Engineering International Online, Stuart Birch, European Editor \n  | url = http://www.sae.org/automag/globalvehicles/11-2001/}}</ref> Referring to the trend in a 2004 article, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' noted an advantage: \"the higher the H-Point, the higher you ride in the car, and in some cases, the more comfortable you feel behind the wheel\".<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\nBuses, [[minivan]]s, [[SUV]]s and [[Crossover SUV|CUV]]s generally have higher H-points (relative to the road surface and the vehicle interior floor) than [[sedan (car)|sedan]]s, though certain sedans feature higher H-points than most, e.g., the [[Ford Five Hundred]], [[Fiat 500L]]. Sports cars and vehicles with higher aerodynamic considerations, by contrast, may employ lower H-points relative to the road surface. When an automobile features progressively higher H-points at each successive seating row, the seating is called [[stadium seating]], as in the  [[Dodge Journey]], and [[Ford Flex]].<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\nVehicle interior ergonomics are integral to an automotive design education. The [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] (SAE) has adopted tools for vehicle design, including statistical models for predicting driver eye location and seat position as well as an H-point [[mannequin]] for measuring seats and interior package geometry. See SAE J86 for a description of the H-point machine. Occupant posture-prediction models are used in computer simulations and form the basis for [[crash test dummy]] positioning.<ref name=\"UMTRI\">{{cite web\n  | title = Vehicle Ergonomics Laboratories\n  | publisher = U. Michigan Transportation Research Institute\n  | url = http://www.umtri.umich.edu/facilityPage.php?fID=21}}</ref>\n\n'''Regulatory definition:'''  For the purpose of U.S. regulation and GTRs (Global Technical Regulations)&nbsp;&ndash; and for clear communication in safety and seating design<ref name=\"rpoint\">{{cite web\n  | title = NHTSA's Activities under the United Nations for Europe 1998 Global Agreement: Head Restraints, Docket NHTSA-2008-001600001\n  | publisher = NHTSA \n  | url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/2752327/Notice-Activities-Under-the-United-Nations-Economic-Commission-for-Europe-1998-Global-Agreement-Head-Restraints}}</ref>&nbsp;&ndash; the H-point is defined as the actual hip point of the seated crash test dummy itself,<ref name=\"rpoint\"/> whereas the '''R-point''' (or SgRP, seating reference point) is the theoretical hip point used by manufacturers when designing a vehicle&nbsp;&ndash; and more specifically describes the relative location of the seated dummy's hip point when the seat is set in the rearmost and lowermost seating position.<ref name=\"rpoint\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ergonomics]]\n*[[Anthropometry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bmpcoe.org/bestpractices/internal/sae/grf_sae_08.html SAE Three Dimensional H-Point Engineering Aid Support]\n*[http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedan/112_0412_american_sedan_comparison/advances.html Motor Trend: Three Advances In The Art Of The Sedan]\n\n[[Category:Automotive design]]\n[[Category:Automotive styling features]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:H-Point (rev).PNG|280px|right]]  \nThe '''H-point''' (or '''hip-point''') is the theoretical, relative location of an occupant's [[Hip (anatomy)|hip]]: specifically the pivot point between the torso and upper leg portions of the body &mdash; as used in vehicle design, [[automotive design]] and vehicle regulation as well as other disciplines including chair and furniture design.  \n\nIn vehicle design, the H-point is also measured ''relative'' to other features, e.g. h-point to vehicle floor ('''H30''')<ref name=\"ref3\">{{cite web\n  | title = 2004 Mitsubishi Outlander New Car Test Drive  | publisher = Car.com, Larry Edsall \n  | url = http://www.car.com/content/Research/Reviews/index.cfm/action/DisplayPro/aid/138805/Make_vch/Mitsubishi/Model_vch/Outlander/Year_si/2004}}</ref> or h-point to pavement ('''H5''').  In other words, a vehicle said to have a \"high H-point\" may have an H-point that is \"high\" ''relative'' to the vehicle floor, the road surface, or both.\n\nTechnically, the h-point measurement uses the hip joint of a 50th [[percentile]] male occupant, viewed laterally,<ref name=\"fed reg\">{{cite web\n  | title = Dept of Transportation NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards\n  | publisher = Federal Register  May 4, 07 p.25485\n  | url = http://edocket.access.gpo.gov/2007/pdf/07-2011.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> and is highly relevant to national and international vehicle design standards such as [[Vehicle regulation|global technical regulations (GTR)]].  For example, a vehicle design standard known as the [[Society of Automotive Engineers|Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE)]] '''J1100 Interior Measurement Index''' sets parameters for such measurements as '''H30''' (H-point to vehicle floor); '''H5''' (H-point to pavement surface), '''H61''' (H-point to interior ceiling) and '''H25''' (H-point to window sill).<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Riding High: Auto Makers Jack Up the Car Seat; Finding Your Ideal 'H-Point'\n |publisher    = The Wall Street Journal\n |author       = Michelle Higgins\n |date         = December 2, 2004\n |url          = https://www.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB110194232087888545.html\n |access-date  = March 13, 2017\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080502202118/http://online.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB110194232087888545.html\n |archive-date = May 2, 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref> \n\nAs with the location of other automotive design \"hard points,\" the H-point has major ramifications in the overall vehicle design, including roof height, aerodynamics, visibility (both within the vehicle and from the vehicle into traffic), seating comfort,<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web\n  | title = 2005 Ford Freestyle Design\n  | publisher = Myfordfreestyle.com\n  | url = http://www.myfordfreestyle.com/specs/2005_freestyle_design.php}}</ref> driver fatigue, ease of entry and exit,<ref name=\"ref1\"/> interior packaging, [[Automobile safety|safety]], restraint and airbag design and collision performance.  As an example, higher H-points can provide more legroom, both in the front and back seats.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\nBy the early 2000s there had been a global trend toward higher H-points ''relative'' to the road surface and the vehicle's interior floor.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web\n  | title = Frankfurt Motor Show: Will getting more into less become more out of less?\n  | publisher = Automotive Engineering International Online, Stuart Birch, European Editor \n  | url = http://www.sae.org/automag/globalvehicles/11-2001/}}</ref> Referring to the trend in a 2004 article, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' noted an advantage: \"the higher the H-Point, the higher you ride in the car, and in some cases, the more comfortable you feel behind the wheel\".<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\nBuses, [[minivan]]s, [[SUV]]s and [[Crossover SUV|CUV]]s generally have higher H-points (relative to the road surface and the vehicle interior floor) than [[sedan (car)|sedan]]s, though certain sedans feature higher H-points than most, e.g., the [[Ford Five Hundred]], [[Fiat 500L]]. Sports cars and vehicles with higher aerodynamic considerations, by contrast, may employ lower H-points relative to the road surface. When an automobile features progressively higher H-points at each successive seating row, the seating is called [[stadium seating]], as in the  [[Dodge Journey]], and [[Ford Flex]].<ref name=\"ref1\"/>\n\nVehicle interior ergonomics are integral to an automotive design education. The [[Society of Automotive Engineers]] (SAE) has adopted tools for vehicle design, including statistical models for predicting driver eye location and seat position as well as an H-point [[mannequin]] for measuring seats and interior package geometry. See SAE J86 for a description of the H-point machine. Occupant posture-prediction models are used in computer simulations and form the basis for [[crash test dummy]] positioning.<ref name=\"UMTRI\">{{cite web\n  | title = Vehicle Ergonomics Laboratories\n  | publisher = U. Michigan Transportation Research Institute\n  | url = http://www.umtri.umich.edu/facilityPage.php?fID=21}}</ref>\n\n'''Regulatory definition:'''  For the purpose of U.S. regulation and GTRs (Global Technical Regulations)&nbsp;&ndash; and for clear communication in safety and seating design<ref name=\"rpoint\">{{cite web\n  | title = NHTSA's Activities under the United Nations for Europe 1998 Global Agreement: Head Restraints, Docket NHTSA-2008-001600001\n  | publisher = NHTSA \n  | url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/2752327/Notice-Activities-Under-the-United-Nations-Economic-Commission-for-Europe-1998-Global-Agreement-Head-Restraints}}</ref>&nbsp;&ndash; the H-point is defined as the actual hip point of the seated crash test dummy itself,<ref name=\"rpoint\"/> whereas the '''R-point''' (or SgRP, seating reference point) is the theoretical hip point used by manufacturers when designing a vehicle&nbsp;&ndash; and more specifically describes the relative location of the seated dummy's hip point when the seat is set in the rearmost and lowermost seating position.<ref name=\"rpoint\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ergonomics]]\n*[[Anthropometry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bmpcoe.org/bestpractices/internal/sae/grf_sae_08.html SAE Three Dimensional H-Point Engineering Aid Support]\n*[http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/sedan/112_0412_american_sedan_comparison/advances.html Motor Trend: Three Advances In The Art Of The Sedan]\n\n[[Category:Automotive design]]\n[[Category:Automotive styling features]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H-point"}
{"title_page": "Deborah Steinberg", "text_new": "{{short description|American Antarctic biological oceanographer}}\n{{for|the sociologist|Deborah Lynn Steinberg}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Deborah Steinberg\n| image = <!-- http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/_images/steinberg_rothera_200.jpg --> <!-- Need to request image from Steinberg -->\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Deborah Steinberg at South Pole\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| nationality = American-Antarctic\n| fields = [[Oceanography]]\n| workplaces = [[Virginia Institute of Marine Science]], The College of William and Mary\n| alma_mater = B.A. [[University of California Santa Barbara]]\nPh.D. [[University of California Santa Cruz]]\n| known_for = Interdisciplinary oceanography and zooplankton ecology\n| awards = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.vims.edu/people/steinberg_dk|Deborah Steinberg at VIMS}}\n}}\n\n'''Deborah K. Steinberg''' is an American [[Antarctic]] biological [[Oceanography|oceanographer]] who works on interdisciplinary oceanographic research programs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/science/dp-nws-antarctic-documentary-vims-20150920-story.html|title=VIMS Antarctic research part of new documentary|last=Dietrich|first=Tamara|website=dailypress.com|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Steinberg's research focuses on the role that [[zooplankton]] play in marine [[food web]]s and the global [[carbon cycle]], and how these small drifting animals are affected by changes in climate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schev.edu/adminfaculty/OFA/2015/Steinberg.asp |title=Deborah Steinberg |website=State Council of Higher Education for Virginia |publisher=Virginia.gov |access-date=19 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408212326/http://www.schev.edu/AdminFaculty/OFA/2015/Steinberg.asp |archivedate=8 April 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pices.int/meetings/international_symposia/2011/zoop5/speakers.aspx|title=5th International Zooplankton Symposium|website=www.pices.int|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSteinberg received her B.A. at the [[University of California, Santa Barbara|University of California Santa Barbara]] in 1987. During her undergraduate studies she was a member of a science team for winter research expedition in Antarctica. She received a PhD at the [[University of California, Santa Cruz|University of California Santa Cruz]] in 1993 focusing on zooplankton and marine dynamics.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fondriest.com/news/qa-debbie-steinberg-explains-zooplankton-research-in-a-changing-antarctic.htm|title=Debbie Steingberg Explains Zooplankton Research|last=Kelly|first=Daniel|date=2013-01-18|website=Environmental Monitor|language=en-US|publication-date=2013-01-18|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> After graduation she joined the [[Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences]] as a Research Scientist where she remained until 2001. She then joined the [[Virginia Institute of Marine Science]]s, where she is a CSX Professor of Marine Science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/people/steinberg_dk/|title=Deborah K. Steinberg|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career and impact ==\nSteinberg has been an international leader in understanding the zooplankton and [[jellyfish]] ecology along with how the food web structures the [[Carbon flux|flux of carbon]] to the deep sea.&nbsp;She is currently{{When|date=June 2017}} the lead in the US [[National Science Foundation]] Long-Term Ecological Research ([[Long Term Ecological Research Network|LTER]]) program focused on understanding how rapid warming drives ecosystem change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://antarcticsun.usap.gov/science/contentHandler.cfm?id=2162|title=Back in Time|last=Rejcek|first=Peter|date=June 18, 2010|website=AntarcticSun.USAP.gov|publisher=The Antarctic Sun|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHer research program focuses on how zooplankton influence [[Nutrient cycle|cycling of nutrients]] and organic matter, and how climate affects long-term change in zooplankton communities. Steinberg's laboratory has been involved in a number of projects with this theme, including the role of zooplankton [[Diel vertical migration|vertical migration]] in transport of nutrients, the ecology of gelatinous zooplankton \"blooms\" and their effect on fluxes of organic matter, the importance of zooplankton in the cycling of dissolved organic matter, [[Mesopelagic zone|mesopelagic]] zooplankton and particle flux, and the effects of mesoscale eddies and a large river plume on zooplankton community structure.<ref name=\":3\" /> They are also using long-term data sets from the Western [[Antarctic Peninsula]] and the [[Sargasso Sea]] off Bermuda to study the effects of climate change on zooplankton communities, and how these community changes may affect ocean food webs and [[biogeochemistry]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.earthisland.org/journal/index.php/elist/eListRead/in_review_antarctic_edge_70_south/|title=In Review: Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South|website=www.earthisland.org|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg has worked in a number of marine environments including [[coastal California]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/archives/2012/fish_poop.php|title=Study Shows Small Fish Can Play a Big Role in the Coastal Carbon Cycle|last=Malmquist|first=David|date=9 October 2012|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> [[Antarctic]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/research/units/labgroups/zooplankton_ecology/research/pal_lter.php|title=Palmer Long Term Ecological Research|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> [[Sargasso Sea]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/research/units/labgroups/zooplankton_ecology/research/bats-zooplankton-census.php|title=BATS Zooplankton Census|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> the subtropical and subarctic North Pacific, the [[Amazon River|Amazon River plume]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/archives/2010/anacondas.php|title=ANACONDAS Project Brings VIMS to the Amazon Plume|last=Malmquist|first=David|date=14 May 2010|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> and the [[Chesapeake Bay]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/archives/2005/twilight_zone.php|title=VIMS Researchers Re-Enter Ocean \"Twilight Zone\"|last=Malmquist|first=Dave|date=21 July 2005|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> In the Antarctic, she oversees the [[krill]] research of Kim Bernard and her team known as \"The Psycho Krillers\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/13/science/tracking-antarctic-krill-as-more-is-harvested-for-omega-3-pills.html|title=Team Tracks a Food Supply at the End of the World|last=Moran|first=Susan|date=12 March 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=19 May 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg has spent collectively more than 1.5 years at sea on more than 50 research cruises, and starred in the documentary \"Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South|date=June 1, 2015|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2780714/|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beyondtheice.rutgers.edu/|title=Antarctic Edge: 70 Degrees South|website=Rutgers.edu|language=en-US|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Projects ==\n* [[Long Term Ecological Research Network]]: Land-shelf-ocean connectivity, ecosystem resilience, and transformation in a sea-ice influenced pelagic ecosystem (NSF OPP)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pal.lternet.edu/|title=Palmer Station Antarctica LTER|last=|first=|date=|website=Palmer LTER|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study|The Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study]]: Sustained Biogeochemical, Ecosystem, and Ocean Change Observations and Linkages in the Subtropical North Atlantic (NSF&nbsp;OCE)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bats.bios.edu/index.html|title=Overview of BATS|last=|first=|date=|website=Bermuda Atlantic Time-Series Study|publisher=Bermuda Institute of Ocean Science|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n* CSBR: Natural History: Organization and digitization of the larval fish collection at the Virginia Institute of Marine Science (NSF DBI)\n* Jellyfish population dynamics in the [[Chesapeake Bay]] (Graduate Fellow - Joshua Stone) (Virginia Sea Grant, NOAA)\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 2015 - [[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia]] ([[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia|SCHEV]]) Outstanding Faculty Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/steinberg_ofa.php|title=Steinberg receives Virginia Outstanding Faculty Award|website=www.vims.edu|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n* 2014 - CSX Eminent Scholar Professorship/ Chair in Marine Science\n* 2014 - William & Mary [[Joe J. Plumeri|Plumeri Award for Faculty Excellence]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2014/william--mary-announces-2014-recipients-of-plumeri-awards-for-faculty-excellence-123.php|title=W&M Announces 2014 Recipients of Plumeri Awards for Faculty Excellence|last=Langhorne|first=Nicholas|date=3 April 2014|website=William & Mary|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 - William & Mary Tack Faculty lecture\n* 2012 - Sverdrup Award lecture, Ocean Sciences, [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU)\n* 2007 - Winner of William and Mary [[Balloon debate|Raft Debate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wm.edu/as/graduate/graduate-center/RaftDebate/|title=The Raft Debate|website=www.wm.edu|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* 2006 - Dean's Prize for Advancement of Women in Marine Science\n* 2005 - College of William & Mary Class of 1964 Distinguished Associate Professor of Marine Science\n* 2005 - Elected to the board of trustees, [[Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences]], Inc.\n* 1987 - [[National Science Foundation]] Antarctic Service Award and Medal\n\n== Professional Memberships ==\n* [[American Society of Limnology and Oceanography]] (ASLO)\n* [[The Oceanography Society]] (TOS)\n* [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU)\n\n==Selected works==\n*Steinberg, Deborah K., et al. \"Overview of the US JGOFS Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study (BATS): a decade-scale look at ocean biology and biogeochemistry.\" Deep-Sea Research Part II: Topical Studies in Oceanography 48.8 (2001): 1405-1447.\n*Steinberg, Deborah A., et al. \"Protegrin-1: a broad-spectrum, rapidly microbicidal peptide with in vivo activity.\" Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy 41.8 (1997): 1738-1742.\n*Steinberg, Deborah K., et al. \"Zooplankton vertical migration and the active transport of dissolved organic and inorganic carbon in the Sargasso Sea.\" Deep-Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers 47.1 (2000): 137-158.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ydHSvQ6j2MM Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South]'', Documentary trailer\n* [http://www.vims.edu/people/steinberg_dk/ Deborah Steinberg's webpage]\n* {{google scholar id|nKw_gY4AAAAJ}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steinberg, Deborah}}\n[[Category:Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:Women oceanographers]]\n[[Category:American oceanographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Antarctic biological oceanographer}}\n{{for|the sociologist|Deborah Lynn Steinberg}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Deborah Steinberg\n| image = <!-- http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/_images/steinberg_rothera_200.jpg --> <!-- Need to request image from Steinberg -->\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Deborah Steinberg at South Pole\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| nationality = American-Antarctic\n| fields = [[Oceanography]]\n| workplaces = [[Virginia Institute of Marine Science]], The College of William and Mary\n| alma_mater = B.A. [[University of California Santa Barbara]]\nPh.D. [[University of California Santa Cruz]]\n| known_for = Interdisciplinary oceanography and zooplankton ecology\n| awards = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.vims.edu/people/steinberg_dk|Deborah Steinberg at VIMS}}\n}}\n\n'''Deborah K. Steinberg''' is an American [[Antarctic]] biological [[Oceanography|oceanographer]] who works on interdisciplinary oceanographic research programs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/news/science/dp-nws-antarctic-documentary-vims-20150920-story.html|title=VIMS Antarctic research part of new documentary|last=Dietrich|first=Tamara|website=dailypress.com|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> Steinberg's research focuses on the role that [[zooplankton]] play in marine [[food web]]s and the global [[carbon cycle]], and how these small drifting animals are affected by changes in climate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schev.edu/adminfaculty/OFA/2015/Steinberg.asp |title=Deborah Steinberg |website=State Council of Higher Education for Virginia |publisher=Virginia.gov |access-date=19 May 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408212326/http://www.schev.edu/AdminFaculty/OFA/2015/Steinberg.asp |archivedate=8 April 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pices.int/meetings/international_symposia/2011/zoop5/speakers.aspx|title=5th International Zooplankton Symposium|website=www.pices.int|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSteinberg received her B.A. at the [[University of California, Santa Barbara|University of California Santa Barbara]] in 1987. During her undergraduate studies she was a member of a science team for winter research expedition in Antarctica. She received a PhD at the [[University of California, Santa Cruz|University of California Santa Cruz]] in 1993 focusing on zooplankton and marine dynamics.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fondriest.com/news/qa-debbie-steinberg-explains-zooplankton-research-in-a-changing-antarctic.htm|title=Debbie Steingberg Explains Zooplankton Research|last=Kelly|first=Daniel|date=2013-01-18|website=Environmental Monitor|language=en-US|publication-date=2013-01-18|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref> After graduation she joined the [[Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences]] as a Research Scientist where she remained until 2001. She then joined the [[Virginia Institute of Marine Science]]s, where she is a CSX Professor of Marine Science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/people/steinberg_dk/|title=Deborah K. Steinberg|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Career and impact ==\nSteinberg has been an international leader in understanding the zooplankton and [[jellyfish]] ecology along with how the food web structures the [[Carbon flux|flux of carbon]] to the deep sea.&nbsp;She is currently{{When|date=June 2017}} the lead in the US [[National Science Foundation]] Long-Term Ecological Research ([[Long Term Ecological Research Network|LTER]]) program focused on understanding how rapid warming drives ecosystem change.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://antarcticsun.usap.gov/science/contentHandler.cfm?id=2162|title=Back in Time|last=Rejcek|first=Peter|date=June 18, 2010|website=AntarcticSun.USAP.gov|publisher=The Antarctic Sun|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHer research program focuses on how zooplankton influence [[Nutrient cycle|cycling of nutrients]] and organic matter, and how climate affects long-term change in zooplankton communities. Steinberg's laboratory has been involved in a number of projects with this theme, including the role of zooplankton [[Diel vertical migration|vertical migration]] in transport of nutrients, the ecology of gelatinous zooplankton \"blooms\" and their effect on fluxes of organic matter, the importance of zooplankton in the cycling of dissolved organic matter, [[Mesopelagic zone|mesopelagic]] zooplankton and particle flux, and the effects of mesoscale eddies and a large river plume on zooplankton community structure.<ref name=\":3\" /> They are also using long-term data sets from the Western [[Antarctic Peninsula]] and the [[Sargasso Sea]] off Bermuda to study the effects of climate change on zooplankton communities, and how these community changes may affect ocean food webs and [[biogeochemistry]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.earthisland.org/journal/index.php/elist/eListRead/in_review_antarctic_edge_70_south/|title=In Review: Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South|website=www.earthisland.org|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg has worked in a number of marine environments including [[coastal California]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/archives/2012/fish_poop.php|title=Study Shows Small Fish Can Play a Big Role in the Coastal Carbon Cycle|last=Malmquist|first=David|date=9 October 2012|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> [[Antarctic]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/research/units/labgroups/zooplankton_ecology/research/pal_lter.php|title=Palmer Long Term Ecological Research|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> [[Sargasso Sea]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/research/units/labgroups/zooplankton_ecology/research/bats-zooplankton-census.php|title=BATS Zooplankton Census|last=|first=|date=|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> the subtropical and subarctic North Pacific, the [[Amazon River|Amazon River plume]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/archives/2010/anacondas.php|title=ANACONDAS Project Brings VIMS to the Amazon Plume|last=Malmquist|first=David|date=14 May 2010|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> and the [[Chesapeake Bay]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/archives/2005/twilight_zone.php|title=VIMS Researchers Re-Enter Ocean \"Twilight Zone\"|last=Malmquist|first=Dave|date=21 July 2005|website=Virginia Institute of Marine Science|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref> In the Antarctic, she oversees the [[krill]] research of Kim Bernard and her team known as \"The Psycho Krillers\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/13/science/tracking-antarctic-krill-as-more-is-harvested-for-omega-3-pills.html|title=Team Tracks a Food Supply at the End of the World|last=Moran|first=Susan|date=12 March 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=19 May 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg has spent collectively more than 1.5 years at sea on more than 50 research cruises, and starred in the documentary \"Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South|date=June 1, 2015|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2780714/|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beyondtheice.rutgers.edu/|title=Antarctic Edge: 70 Degrees South|website=Rutgers.edu|language=en-US|access-date=May 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Projects ==\n* [[Long Term Ecological Research Network]]: Land-shelf-ocean connectivity, ecosystem resilience, and transformation in a sea-ice influenced pelagic ecosystem (NSF OPP)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pal.lternet.edu/|title=Palmer Station Antarctica LTER|last=|first=|date=|website=Palmer LTER|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study|The Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study]]: Sustained Biogeochemical, Ecosystem, and Ocean Change Observations and Linkages in the Subtropical North Atlantic (NSF&nbsp;OCE)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bats.bios.edu/index.html|title=Overview of BATS|last=|first=|date=|website=Bermuda Atlantic Time-Series Study|publisher=Bermuda Institute of Ocean Science|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n* CSBR: Natural History: Organization and digitization of the larval fish collection at the Virginia Institute of Marine Science (NSF DBI)\n* Jellyfish population dynamics in the [[Chesapeake Bay]] (Graduate Fellow - Joshua Stone) (Virginia Sea Grant, NOAA)\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n* 2015 - [[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia]] ([[State Council of Higher Education for Virginia|SCHEV]]) Outstanding Faculty Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vims.edu/newsandevents/topstories/steinberg_ofa.php|title=Steinberg receives Virginia Outstanding Faculty Award|website=www.vims.edu|access-date=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n* 2014 - CSX Eminent Scholar Professorship/ Chair in Marine Science\n* 2014 - William & Mary [[Joe J. Plumeri|Plumeri Award for Faculty Excellence]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2014/william--mary-announces-2014-recipients-of-plumeri-awards-for-faculty-excellence-123.php|title=W&M Announces 2014 Recipients of Plumeri Awards for Faculty Excellence|last=Langhorne|first=Nicholas|date=3 April 2014|website=William & Mary|publisher=|access-date=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 - William & Mary Tack Faculty lecture\n* 2012 - Sverdrup Award lecture, Ocean Sciences, [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU)\n* 2007 - Winner of William and Mary [[Balloon debate|Raft Debate]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wm.edu/as/graduate/graduate-center/RaftDebate/|title=The Raft Debate|website=www.wm.edu|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* 2006 - Dean's Prize for Advancement of Women in Marine Science\n* 2005 - College of William & Mary Class of 1964 Distinguished Associate Professor of Marine Science\n* 2005 - Elected to the board of trustees, [[Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences]], Inc.\n* 1987 - [[National Science Foundation]] Antarctic Service Award and Medal\n\n== Professional Memberships ==\n* [[American Society of Limnology and Oceanography]] (ASLO)\n* [[The Oceanography Society]] (TOS)\n* [[American Geophysical Union]] (AGU)\n\n==Selected works==\n*Steinberg, Deborah K., et al. \"Overview of the US JGOFS Bermuda Atlantic Time-series Study (BATS): a decade-scale look at ocean biology and biogeochemistry.\" Deep-Sea Research Part II: Topical Studies in Oceanography 48.8 (2001): 1405-1447.\n*Steinberg, Deborah A., et al. \"Protegrin-1: a broad-spectrum, rapidly microbicidal peptide with in vivo activity.\" Antimicrobial Agents and Chemotherapy 41.8 (1997): 1738-1742.\n*Steinberg, Deborah K., et al. \"Zooplankton vertical migration and the active transport of dissolved organic and inorganic carbon in the Sargasso Sea.\" Deep-Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers 47.1 (2000): 137-158.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ydHSvQ6j2MM Antarctic Edge: 70\u00b0 South]'', Documentary trailer\n* [http://www.vims.edu/people/steinberg_dk/ Deborah Steinberg's webpage]\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=nKw_gY4AAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao Deborah Steinberg] on [[Google Scholar|Google scholar]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steinberg, Deborah}}\n[[Category:Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women Antarctic scientists]]\n[[Category:Women oceanographers]]\n[[Category:American oceanographers]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deborah_Steinberg"}
{"title_page": "USACFC", "text_new": "[[File:Official 2010 USACFC Logo.jpg | right | Official 2010 USACFC logo by James Preimesberger, Swarthmore College Fencing Team]]\nThe United States Association of Collegiate Fencing Clubs ('''USACFC''') was established in 2003<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usacfc.org/about-usacfc|title=USACFC|website=www.usacfc.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> to educate and promote fencing at the collegiate level throughout the United States.\u00a0The organization began with 13 teams and has grown to over 45 teams since its inception.\n\nUSACFC was formed as a Pennsylvania Nonprofit Corporation in 2005.\u00a0 Each year the organization holds a national fencing championship in the host city of one of the member colleges.\n\n== Champions ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Combined Team !! Women's Team !! Men's Team\n|-\n| 2003 || [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] || [[University of Florida]] || \n|-\n| 2004 || [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] || [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] || \n|-\n| 2005 || [[United States Military Academy]] || [[United States Military Academy]] ||\n|-\n| 2006 || [[University of Michigan]] || [[University of Michigan]] ||\n|-\n| 2007 || [[University of Michigan]] || [[University of Michigan]] ||\n|-\n| 2008 || [[Arizona State University]] || [[University of Florida]] ||\n|-\n| 2009 || [[University of Florida]] || [[University of Florida]] || [[College of William & Mary|William and Mary]]\n|-\n| 2010 || [[University of Florida]] || [[University of Florida]] || [[Northwestern University]]\n|-\n| 2011 || [[University of Florida]] || [[University of Florida]] || [[Northwestern University]]\n|-\n| 2012 || [[University of Florida]] || [[University of Florida]] || [[University of Michigan]]\n|-\n| 2013 || [[University of Michigan]] || [[University of Michigan]] || [[University of Michigan]]\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Dartmouth College]] || [[United States Naval Academy]] || [[Dartmouth College]]\n|-\n| 2015 