{"title_page": "Canada\u2013Cuba relations", "text_new": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between Canada and the Republic of Cuba}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations\n| title       = Canada\u2013Cuba\n| party1      = Canada\n| party2      = Cuba\n| map         = Canada Cuba Locator.png\n| filetype    = png\n| size        = 220\n| mission1    = Canadian Embassy, Havana\n| mission2    = [[Embassy of Cuba, Ottawa|Cuban Embassy, Ottawa]]\n| envoytitle1 = Ambassador\n| envoy1      = Perry Calderwood<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/global-affairs/news/2019/05/diplomatic-appointments.html|title=Diplomatic appointments - Perry Calderwood and Patrick Parisot|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019|work=Global Affairs Canada|publisher=Government of Canada}}</ref>\n| envoytitle2 = Ambassador\n| envoy2      = [[Josefina Vidal]]\n}}\n'''Canada\u2013Cuba relations''' refers to the [[bilateralism|bilateral relationship]] between [[Canada]] and [[Cuba]]. Informal trade relations between the colonies of [[Atlantic Canada]], and the [[Captaincy General of Cuba]] has existed since the 18th century. However, diplomatic relations between Canada and Cuba was not formally established until 1945.\n\nDiplomatic relations between Canada and Cuba remains uninterrupted since it was established in 1945, with Canada being one of the only two countries in the [[Americas]] to maintain relations with Cuba after the [[Cuban Revolution]] in 1959. Relations between the Canada and Cuba had become an occasional point of contention for [[Canada-United States relations]].\n\nBoth countries maintain embassies in the other's respective capital city, in addition to consulates in other cities. Canada is Cuba's largest source for tourists, with Canadians accounting for 30 per cent of tourists who visit the country. Conversely Cuba is Canada's second largest export partner in the [[Caribbean]]/[[Central America]]n region.\n\n==History==\nTrade relations between Canada and Cuba dates back to the 18th century, with vessels from [[Atlantic Canada]] trading cod and beer for rum and sugar in Cuba.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/cuba/bilateral_relations_bilaterales/index.aspx?lang=eng|title=Canada - Cuba Relations|publisher=Government of Canada|date=1 June 2018|accessdate=25 July 2019|work=Embassy of Canada to Cuba}}</ref> Diplomatic relations was formally established between the two countries in 1945.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/> Cuba was the first country in the [[Caribbean]] selected by Canada for a diplomatic mission.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/>\n\n===Post-Cuban Revolution===\n[[File:John G. Diefenbaker.jpg|thumb|upright|[[John Diefenbaker]], [[Prime Minister of Canada]], decided to maintain relations with Cuba in the aftermath of the [[Cuban Revolution]].]]\nDiplomatic relations between the Canada and Cuba remained uninterrupted in the aftermath of the [[Cuban Revolution]].<ref name=CBC1>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/entry/viva-cuba-trudeau-goes-abroad|title=Viva Cuba: Trudeau goes abroad|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|work=CBC Archives|year=2018|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Canada, in addition to Mexico, remained one of only two countries in the [[Americas]] that maintained uninterrupted relations with Cuba after the revolution.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/> Although [[John Diefenbaker]], the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], was a staunch anti-[[communist]], he reasoned that relations should be continued \"despite the philosophical differences between [Cuba's] communist regime and [[Western world|the West]]..., and that Canada should hardly be required to tighten its trade restrictions above and beyond those of other Latin American nations.\"<ref name=book>{{cite book|pages=75\u201395|title=Our Place in the Sun: Canada and Cuba in the Castro Era|chapter=Calculated Diplomacy': John Diefenbaker and the Origins of Canada's Cuba Policy|first=Dennis|last=Molinaro|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=0-8020-9666-2|year=2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 1959,  the [[Prime Minister of Cuba]], [[Fidel Castro]],{{notetag|name=Cast|Castro governed Cuba as the Prime Minister of the country from 1959 to 1976. He governed the country as the [[Council of State (Cuba)|Council of State]] from 1976 to 2008.}} visited [[Montreal]] to participate in a toy drive for Cuban children. In addition to inviting Castro, the event's organizers, the Junior Chamber of Commerce of Montreal, also invited several members of Canadian government to greet Castro, although those contacted refused to do so.<ref name=montvis>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/fidel-castro-visit-montreal-april-1959-1.3871200|title=How 1 man brought Fidel Castro to Montreal in April 1959|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=29 July 2019|date=28 November 2016|first=Brennan|last=Neill}}</ref>\n\nThe choice to maintain relations with the revolutionary Cuban government served as a point of contention for [[Canada-United States relations|Canada-U.S. relations]] in the decades following the Cuban Revolution. During [[John F. Kennedy]]'s tenure as the [[President of the United States]], Diefenbaker used Canadian-Cuban relations to showcase that Canada was not mirroring the [[foreign policy of the United States]].<ref name=book/>\n\n====Cuban Missile Crisis====\nCanada played a minor role in the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], with the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] assisting the United States, and other [[NATO]] allies in searching the North Atlantic Ocean for Soviet vessels from the 24 October to the end of the crisis.<ref name=cmc>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/cuban-missile-crisis|title=Caanda and the Cuban Missile Crisis|publisher=Historica Canada|date=9 September 2019|accessdate=10 December 2019|last=Stairs|first=Denis|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia}}</ref> However, Diefenbaker's desire to maintain an independent foreign policy from the United States during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], contributed towards his defeat [[1963 Canadian federal election]]. Prior to the U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]] making a public televised announcement of its Cuban quarantine on 22 October 1962, Kennedy had called Diefenbaker to inform him about the plan, and to request Canadian Forces be placed on DEFCON-3.<ref name=cmc/> Diefenbaker in turn was angered that his government was not consulted earlier; and questioned Kennedy for further proof, and to first send a [[United Nations]] team to confirm it.<ref name=cmc/> The issue led to a two-day debate in Diefenbaker's cabinet, with [[Minister of National Defence (Canada)|Minister of National Defence]] [[Douglas Harkness]] advocating that Canada follow the United States in raising its military readiness, given their \"obligations\" as members of NATO, and [[NORAD]].<ref name=cmc/>\n\nHarkness's position eventually gained the support from Diefenbaker's cabinet as Soviet ships approached the American quarantine zone, and other NATO members began to voice their support for the United States.<ref name=cmc/> DEFCON-3 was formally authorized by Diefenbaker on 24 October.<ref name=cmc/> Diefenbaker's public perception in Canada suffered from the crisis, with the Canadian public viewing Diefenbaker as indecisive.<ref name=cmc/> The perception as an indecisive leader, and his refusal to accept nuclear-armed [[CIM-10 Bomarc]] missiles, led to his eventual defeat to [[Lester B. Pearson]]'s [[Liberal Party of Canada]] in the 1963 election.<ref name=cmc/>\n\n====Post Cuban Missile Crisis====\nAlthough Diefenbaker was defeated in the 1963 election, his policy with Cuba was continued by the Liberal Party most notably under the tenure of Prime Minister [[Pierre Trudeau]], who long held the opinion that Canada needed to establish a foreign policy, \"independent of American influence\".<ref name=CBC1/>\n\nThe Canadian government was critical of the [[United States embargo against Cuba]] during the 1960s and 1970s, objecting to American attempts to block trade to Cuba by Canadian-based American subsidiaries.<ref name=wapo/>  In 1975, the United States passed legislation, loosening the restrictions in its embargo, formally permitting foreign subsidiaries of American-based companies to conduct trade with Cuba.<ref name=wapo/>\n\nIn 1976, Trudeau spent three days in Cuba, and sparked a personal friendship with Castro.<ref name=CBC1/><ref name=\"tnic\">{{cite book|title=Three Nights in Havana: Pierre Trudeau, Fidel Castro and the Cold War World|last=Wright|first=Robert|publisher=HarperCollins Canada|year=2010|isbn=1-5546-8931-7}}</ref> The visit was also the first by a Western nation to Cuba since 1960.<ref name=\"tnic\"/> Trudeau's trip to Canada was criticized by Diefenbaker, given Cuba's involvement in the [[Angolan Civil War]]. Remarks made by Trudeau in Cuba, notably \"Viva Cuba! Viva Fidel Castro,\" were also criticized by Diefenbaker, and [[Thomas Cossitt]], a Canadian Member of [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]].<ref name=CBC1/> In his memoirs, Trudeau noted that Castro downplayed Cuba's involvement in Angola during his visit, and he had only realized the extent of Cuba's involvement after returning to [[Ottawa]]. Shortly after his visit to Cuba, Trudeau cut foreign aid to Cuba.<ref name=CBC1/>\n\nIn January 1977, Canadian-Cuban relations was strained after details were made public that the Cuban government used a consular mission in Montreal for the purposes of [[Espionage|information-gathering]].<ref name=wapo>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1977/01/16/spy-scandal-is-souring-canadian-cuban-relations/66009708-d30d-4ab8-886a-ff9fded1dc3c/?noredirect=on|title=Spy Scandal Is Souring Canadian-Cuban Relations|date=16 January 1977|publisher=Nash Holdings|work=The Washington Post|last=Lavnie|first=Michael}}</ref> Five Cuban nationals were expelled from Canada, including three diplomats.<ref name=wapo/> Canadian law enforcement was already aware of the espionage activities within the consulate, and placed the building under surveillance as early as 1972. Although Canadian authorities monitored of the Cuban consulate, they had no intention to move against consulate officials until after details of Cuban espionage were made public; which forced authorities to proceed with their expulsion.<ref name=wapo/> In a statement of admission, the Cuban government stated it used the consulate for intelligence gathering, although noted its activities were directed against the United States government and the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref name=wapo/>\n\nIn 1984, the Canadian government passed the ''[[Foreign Extraterritorial Measures Act]]'', a law designed to dissuade Canadian-based American subsidiaries from taking part in the American economic embargo of Cuba.<ref name=torst>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2019/04/18/how-venezuela-is-impacting-canadas-relations-with-cuba.html|title=How Venezuela is impacting Canada\u2019s relations with Cuba|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=The Toronto Star|last=Walkom|first=Thomas|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1990s\u2013present===\nIn 1994, a joint venture was formed between the Cuban Nickel Union and the Canadian firm [[Sherritt International]], which operates a mining and processing plant on the island in [[Moa, Cuba|Moa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherritt.com/About-Sherritt/History|title=History of Sherritt|publisher=Sherritt International Corporation|year=2012|access-date=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507031340/http://www.sherritt.com/About-Sherritt/History#|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> A second enterprise, Cobalt Refinery Co. Inc., was created in Alberta for nickel refining.\n\nCanada, in addition to the [[European Union]], objected to the passage of the ''[[Helms-Burton Act]]'' in the U.S. Congress in 1996, specifically Title III, a provision that permitted Americans whose properties were nationalized by the Cuban government, to sue individuals that are presently using it.<ref name=torst/> The [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Canada)|Canadian Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Lloyd Axworthy]] stated \"Canada shares the U.S. objectives of improving human rights standards and moving to more representative government in Cuba. But we are concerned that the Helms-Burton Act takes the wrong approach. That is why we have been working with other countries to uphold the principles of international law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/latin_america/january97/canada_1-23.html|title=Online NewsHour: Lloyd Axworthy|date=23 January 1997|work=Online NewsHour|publisher=Public Broadcasting Service|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themilitant.com/1996/6011/6011_19.html|title=Ottawa Objects To Helms-Burton|last=Dmytryshyn|first=Ned|work=The Militant|date=18 March 1996|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the ''Helms-Burton Act'', the ''Foreign Extraterritorial Measures Act'' was amended to permit Canadians sued under the ''Helms-Burton Act'', to counter-sue in Canadian courts. The resulting amendment also found those that paid damages under the ''Helms-Burton Act'' to be liable to fines and imprisonment in Canada.<ref name=torst/> In a satirical response to the ''Helms-Burton Act'', a [[private member's bill]] known as the [[Godfrey-Milliken Bill]] was introduced in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in response to the extraterritoriality of the ''Helms-Burton Act''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.textfiles.com/politics/NWO/nwo_0012.txt |title=Bill C-339: The Godfrey-Milliken Bill |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618072721/http://web.textfiles.com/politics/NWO/nwo_0012.txt |archivedate=2013-06-18 |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/LegisInfo/BillDetails.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&billId=4771622|title=Private Member's Bill C-339|work=LEGISinfo|publisher=Parliament of Canada|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> The proposed bill would have allowed descendants of [[United Empire Loyalists]] who fled the [[American Revolution]] to be able to reclaim land and property that was confiscated by the American government in the 1700s. Although the ''Helms-Burton Act'' went into effect in 1996, enactment of Title III was postponed until April 2019.<ref name=torst/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1996/7/29/clintons-concession|title=Clinton's concession|work=Maclean's|publisher=Rogers Digital Media|first=Anthony|last=Wilson-Smith|date=29 July 1996|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/cuba/highlights-faits/2019/2019-04-18-helms-burton.aspx?lang=eng|title=Update on the Helms-Burton Act and Canadians doing business in Cuba|publisher=Government of Canada|website=Embassy of Canada to Cuba|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-1990s, Canada and Cuba reached an agreement that saw the Cuban government compensate Canadians whose properties were expropriated after the Cuban Revolution.<ref name=torst/> Emergency economic reforms made during the [[Special Period]] in Cuba, allowed for a significant number of Canadian businesses to invest in Cuba. Increased economic activity between the two countries prompted a 41-hour [[official visit]] to [[Havana]] by Canadian Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] in November 1998.<ref name=GaM>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/castro-and-trudeau-a-famous-but-also-fraught-friendship/article33058005/|title=Castro and Trudeau: a famous, but also fraught friendship|last=Robert|first=Wright|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|accessdate=25 July 2019|date=26 November 2016}}</ref> Chr\u00e9tien faced some criticism in Canada for not publicly voicing his concerns over [[human rights in Cuba]], although he privately discussed the issue with Castro, as well as demanded the release of four specific political dissidents.<ref name=chreitvisi>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/chretien-visits-cuba|title=Chr\u00e9tien visits Cuba|date=15 December 2013|accessdate=10 December 2019|publisher=Historica Canada|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia}}</ref> However, the visit saw no critique levied at Canada from the United States government; with U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] having urged Chr\u00e9tien at the [[24th G8 summit]] months earlier, to raise concerns about human rights to Castro during his planned visit.<ref name=chreitvisi/>\n\nCastro travelled to Montreal in 2000 to serve as one of Trudeau's pallbearers at [[State funeral of Pierre Trudeau|his funeral]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/americas/10/03/canada.castro.reut/index.html|website=CNN.com|publisher=Cable News Network|date=3 October 2000|title=Castro mourns for Trudeau, who stood up for him|accessdate=10 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928052602/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/americas/10/03/canada.castro.reut/index.html|archive-date=28 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====21st century====\nIn 2001, the Canadian government protested U.S. preclearance customs agents in Canadian airports who tried to catch American citizens travelling to Cuba in defiance of U.S. law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibike.org/cuba/ofac/010901-np.htm|first1=Glen|last1=McGregor|first2=Mike|last2=Trickey|title=Canada opposes U.S. crackdown on Cuba visitors|publisher=International Bicycle Fund|date=1 September 2001|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> During the [[2010 United Nations Security Council election]], Cuban diplomats to the United Nations lobbied Latin American ambassadors to the [[United Nations General Assembly]] to vote for Canada.<ref name=macth>{{cite web|url=https://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/canadas-cuban-ties-and-the-washington-havana-thaw/|title=Canada\u2019s Cuban ties and the Washington-Havana thaw|last=Geddes|first=John|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=17 August 2019|work=Maclean's|publisher=Rogers Digital Media}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Canadian government hosted bilateral talks between the governments of Cuba and the United States. Seven negotiation sessions were held between the American and Cuban governments in Ottawa and [[Toronto]].<ref name=macth/> The following negotiations led to the [[Cuban thaw|normalization of relations between the American and Cuban governments]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/facilitating-dialogue-canada-plays-host-to-secret-us-cuban-meetings/article22137559/|title=Facilitiating Dialogue: Canada plays host to secret U.S., Cuban meetings|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=25 July 2019|first=Campbell|last=Clark|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company}}</ref> In November 2016, Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], made a 30-hour official visit to Cuba.<ref name=GaM/>\n\n==Economic relations==\nCuba is presently Canada's second largest export market in the Caribbean/[[Central American]] region, with over [[Canadian dollar|C$]]1 billion in goods traded annually.<ref name=CBC2>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/cuba-castro-succession-diaz-canel-canada-trudeau-1.4624529|title=Cuba's next president won't be a Castro. Here's what that means for Canada.|first=Mark|last=Kwong|work=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> There are in total 85 Canadian companies and subsidiaries operating in Cuba, including brewer [[Labatt Breweries]].\n\nApproximately 1.2 million Canadians visit Cuba annually.<ref name=CBC2/> With Canadian tourists account for 30 per cent of all tourists who visit Cuba per year, Canada is the largest source of tourists for Cuba.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/>\n\n==Diplomatic representation==\n[[File:Embassy of Cuba in Canada (April 2005).jpg|thumb|The [[Embassy of Cuba, Ottawa|Cuban embassy]] in [[Ottawa]].]]\nCanada has had an embassy in Havana since 1945. The current building was built in 1929 and used by Canada since 1961. It also provides consular assistance to Australian and Israeli nationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada-s-embassy-in-cuba-decrepit-says-audit-1.449604|title=Canada's embassy in Cuba decrepit, says audit|date=1 November 2009|accessdate=2 September 2017|work=CTV News|publisher=BellMedia}}</ref> The embassy is located in the upscale district of [[Miramar, Havana|Miramar]] in municipal area of Playa in Havana. Canadian consulates are also found in [[Varadero]] and [[Holguin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.gc.ca/assistance/embassies-consulates/cuba|title=Embassies and consulates: Cuba|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> due to these two locations being key destinations for Canadian tourists.\n\nCuba has an [[Embassy of Cuba, Ottawa|embassy in Ottawa]] and consulates in Montreal, and Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinMontreal.aspx|title=Consulate General of Cuba in Montreal|work=Embassy of Cuba in Canada|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Cuba|access-date=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414115649/http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinMontreal.aspx#|archive-date=14 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinToronto.aspx|title=Consulate General of Cuba in Toronto|work=Embassy of Cuba in Canada|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Cuba|access-date=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414110040/http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinToronto.aspx#|archive-date=14 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Canada\u2013Caribbean relations]]\n*[[Canada\u2013Latin America relations]]\n*[[Cuban Canadian]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Canada]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Cuba]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/cuba/index.aspx?lang=eng Embassy of Canada in Havana]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130214012850/http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Home.aspx Embassy of Cuba in Canada]\n\n{{Foreign relations of Canada}}\n{{Foreign relations of Cuba}}\n{{Portal bar|Canada|Cuba|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Canada-Cuba relations}}\n[[Category:Canada\u2013Cuba relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Canada|Cuba]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Cuba]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1=Diplomatic relations between Canada and the Republic of Cuba}}\n{{Infobox bilateral relations\n| title       = Canada\u2013Cuba\n| party1      = Canada\n| party2      = Cuba\n| map         = Canada Cuba Locator.png\n| filetype    = png\n| size        = 220\n| mission1    = Canadian Embassy, Havana\n| mission2    = [[Embassy of Cuba, Ottawa|Cuban Embassy, Ottawa]]\n| envoytitle1 = Ambassador\n| envoy1      = Perry Calderwood<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/global-affairs/news/2019/05/diplomatic-appointments.html|title=Diplomatic appointments - Perry Calderwood and Patrick Parisot|date=9 May 2019|accessdate=28 July 2019|work=Global Affairs Canada|publisher=Government of Canada}}</ref>\n| envoytitle2 = Ambassador\n| envoy2      = [[Josefina Vidal]]\n}}\n'''Canada\u2013Cuba relations''' refers to the [[bilateralism|bilateral relationship]] between [[Canada]] and [[Cuba]]. Informal trade relations between the colonies of [[Atlantic Canada]], and the [[Captaincy General of Cuba]] has existed since the 18th century. However, diplomatic relations between Canada and Cuba was not formally established until 1945.\n\nDiplomatic relations between Canada and Cuba remains uninterrupted since it was established in 1945, with Canada being one of the only two countries in the [[Americas]] to maintain relations with Cuba after the [[Cuban Revolution]] in 1959. Relations between the Canada and Cuba had become an occasional point of contention for [[Canada-United States relations]].\n\nBoth countries maintain embassies in the other's respective capital city, in addition to consulates in other cities. Canada is Cuba's largest source for tourists, with Canadians accounting for 30 per cent of tourists who visit the country. Conversely Cuba is Canada's second largest export partner in the [[Caribbean]]/[[Central America]]n region.\n\n==History==\nTrade relations between Canada and Cuba dates back to the 18th century, with vessels from [[Atlantic Canada]] trading cod and beer for rum and sugar in Cuba.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/cuba/bilateral_relations_bilaterales/index.aspx?lang=eng|title=Canada - Cuba Relations|publisher=Government of Canada|date=1 June 2018|accessdate=25 July 2019|work=Embassy of Canada to Cuba}}</ref> Diplomatic relations was formally established between the two countries in 1945.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/> Cuba was the first country in the [[Caribbean]] selected by Canada for a diplomatic mission.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/>\n\n===Post-Cuban Revolution===\n[[File:John G. Diefenbaker.jpg|thumb|upright|[[John Diefenbaker]], [[Prime Minister of Canada]], decided to maintain relations with Cuba in the aftermath of the [[Cuban Revolution]].]]\nDiplomatic relations between the Canada and Cuba remained uninterrupted in the aftermath of the [[Cuban Revolution]].<ref name=CBC1>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/archives/entry/viva-cuba-trudeau-goes-abroad|title=Viva Cuba: Trudeau goes abroad|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|work=CBC Archives|year=2018|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Canada, in addition to Mexico, remained one of only two countries in the [[Americas]] that maintained uninterrupted relations with Cuba after the revolution.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/> Although [[John Diefenbaker]], the [[Prime Minister of Canada]], was a staunch anti-[[communist]], he reasoned that relations should be continued \"despite the philosophical differences between [Cuba's] communist regime and [[Western world|the West]]..., and that Canada should hardly be required to tighten its trade restrictions above and beyond those of other Latin American nations.\"<ref name=book>{{cite book|pages=75\u201395|title=Our Place in the Sun: Canada and Cuba in the Castro Era|chapter=Calculated Diplomacy': John Diefenbaker and the Origins of Canada's Cuba Policy|first=Dennis|last=Molinaro|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=0-8020-9666-2|year=2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 April 1959,  the [[Prime Minister of Cuba]], [[Fidel Castro]],{{notetag|name=Cast|Castro governed Cuba as the Prime Minister of the country from 1959 to 1976. He governed the country as the [[Council of State (Cuba)|Council of State]] from 1976 to 2008.}} visited [[Montreal]] to participate in a toy drive for Cuban children. In addition to inviting Castro, the event's organizers, the Junior Chamber of Commerce of Montreal, also invited several members of Canadian government to greet Castro, although those contacted refused to do so.<ref name=montvis>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/fidel-castro-visit-montreal-april-1959-1.3871200|title=How 1 man brought Fidel Castro to Montreal in April 1959|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=29 July 2019|date=28 November 2016|first=Brennan|last=Neill}}</ref>\n\nThe choice to maintain relations with the revolutionary Cuban government served as a point of contention for [[Canada-United States relations|Canada-U.S. relations]] in the decades following the Cuban Revolution. During [[John F. Kennedy]]'s tenure as the [[President of the United States]], Diefenbaker used Canadian-Cuban relations to showcase that Canada was not mirroring the [[foreign policy of the United States]].<ref name=book/> \n\n====Cuban Missile Crisis====\nCanada played a minor role in the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], with the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] assisting the United States, and other [[NATO]] allies in searching the North Atlantic Ocean for Soviet vessels from the 24 October to the end of the crisis.<ref name=cmc>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/cuban-missile-crisis|title=Caanda and the Cuban Missile Crisis|publisher=Historica Canada|date=9 September 2019|accessdate=10 December 2019|last=Stairs|first=Denis|work=The Canadian Encylopedia}}</ref> However, Diefenbaker's desire to maintain an independent foreign policy from the United States during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], contributed towards his defeat [[1963 Canadian federal election]]. Prior to the U.S. President [[John F. Kennedy]] making a public televised announcement of its Cuban quarantine on 22 October 1962, Kennedy had called Diefenbaker to inform him about the plan, and to request Canadian Forces be placed on DEFCON-3.<ref name=cmc/> Diefenbaker in turn was angered that his government was not consulted earlier; and questioned Kennedy for further proof, and to first send a [[United Nations]] team to confirm it.<ref name=cmc/> The issue led to a two-day debate in Diefenbaker's cabinet, with [[Minister of National Defence (Canada)|Minister of National Defence]] [[Douglas Harkness]] advocating that Canada follow the United States in raising its military readiness, given their \"obligations\" as members of NATO, and [[NORAD]].<ref name=cmc/> \n\nHarkness's position eventually gained the support from Diefenbaker's cabinet as Soviet ships approached the American quarantine zone, and other NATO members began to voice their support for the United States.<ref name=cmc/> DEFCON-3 was formally authorized by Diefenbaker on 24 October.<ref name=cmc/> Diefenbaker's public perception in Canada suffered from the crisis, with the Canadian public viewing Diefenbaker as indecisive.<ref name=cmc/> The perception as an indecisive leader, and his refusal to accept nuclear-armed [[CIM-10 Bomarc]] missiles, led to his eventual defeat to [[Lester B. Pearson]]'s [[Liberal Party of Canada]] in the 1963 election.<ref name=cmc/>\n\n====Post Cuban Missile Crisis====\nAlthough Diefenbaker was defeated in the 1963 election, his policy with Cuba was continued by the Liberal Party most notably under the tenure of Prime Minister [[Pierre Trudeau]], who long held the opinion that Canada needed to establish a foreign policy, \"independent of American influence\".<ref name=CBC1/>\n\nThe Canadian government was critical of the [[United States embargo against Cuba]] during the 1960s and 1970s, objecting to American attempts to block trade to Cuba by Canadian-based American subsidiaries.<ref name=wapo/>  In 1975, the United States passed legislation, loosening the restrictions in its embargo, formally permitting foreign subsidiaries of American-based companies to conduct trade with Cuba.<ref name=wapo/>\n\nIn 1976, Trudeau spent three days in Cuba, and sparked a personal friendship with Castro.<ref name=CBC1/><ref name=\"tnic\">{{cite book|title=Three Nights in Havana: Pierre Trudeau, Fidel Castro and the Cold War World|last=Wright|first=Robert|publisher=HarperCollins Canada|year=2010|isbn=1-5546-8931-7}}</ref> The visit was also the first by a Western nation to Cuba since 1960.<ref name=\"tnic\"/> Trudeau's trip to Canada was criticized by Diefenbaker, given Cuba's involvement in the [[Angolan Civil War]]. Remarks made by Trudeau in Cuba, notably \"Viva Cuba! Viva Fidel Castro,\" were also criticized by Diefenbaker, and [[Thomas Cossitt]], a Canadian Member of [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]].<ref name=CBC1/> In his memoirs, Trudeau noted that Castro downplayed Cuba's involvement in Angola during his visit, and he had only realized the extent of Cuba's involvement after returning to [[Ottawa]]. Shortly after his visit to Cuba, Trudeau cut foreign aid to Cuba.<ref name=CBC1/>\n\nIn January 1977, Canadian-Cuban relations was strained after details were made public that the Cuban government used a consular mission in Montreal for the purposes of [[Espionage|information-gathering]].<ref name=wapo>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1977/01/16/spy-scandal-is-souring-canadian-cuban-relations/66009708-d30d-4ab8-886a-ff9fded1dc3c/?noredirect=on|title=Spy Scandal Is Souring Canadian-Cuban Relations|date=16 January 1977|publisher=Nash Holdings|work=The Washington Post|last=Lavnie|first=Michael}}</ref> Five Cuban nationals were expelled from Canada, including three diplomats.<ref name=wapo/> Canadian law enforcement was already aware of the espionage activities within the consulate, and placed the building under surveillance as early as 1972. Although Canadian authorities monitored of the Cuban consulate, they had no intention to move against consulate officials until after details of Cuban espionage were made public; which forced authorities to proceed with their expulsion.<ref name=wapo/> In a statement of admission, the Cuban government stated it used the consulate for intelligence gathering, although noted its activities were directed against the United States government and the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref name=wapo/>\n\nIn 1984, the Canadian government passed the ''[[Foreign Extraterritorial Measures Act]]'', a law designed to dissuade Canadian-based American subsidiaries from taking part in the American economic embargo of Cuba.<ref name=torst>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/star-columnists/2019/04/18/how-venezuela-is-impacting-canadas-relations-with-cuba.html|title=How Venezuela is impacting Canada\u2019s relations with Cuba|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=The Toronto Star|last=Walkom|first=Thomas|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===1990s\u2013present===\nIn 1994, a joint venture was formed between the Cuban Nickel Union and the Canadian firm [[Sherritt International]], which operates a mining and processing plant on the island in [[Moa, Cuba|Moa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherritt.com/About-Sherritt/History|title=History of Sherritt|publisher=Sherritt International Corporation|year=2012|access-date=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507031340/http://www.sherritt.com/About-Sherritt/History#|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> A second enterprise, Cobalt Refinery Co. Inc., was created in Alberta for nickel refining.\n\nCanada, in addition to the [[European Union]], objected to the passage of the ''[[Helms-Burton Act]]'' in the U.S. Congress in 1996, specifically Title III, a provision that permitted Americans whose properties were nationalized by the Cuban government, to sue individuals that are presently using it.<ref name=torst/> The [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Canada)|Canadian Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Lloyd Axworthy]] stated \"Canada shares the U.S. objectives of improving human rights standards and moving to more representative government in Cuba. But we are concerned that the Helms-Burton Act takes the wrong approach. That is why we have been working with other countries to uphold the principles of international law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/latin_america/january97/canada_1-23.html|title=Online NewsHour: Lloyd Axworthy|date=23 January 1997|work=Online NewsHour|publisher=Public Broadcasting Service|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themilitant.com/1996/6011/6011_19.html|title=Ottawa Objects To Helms-Burton|last=Dmytryshyn|first=Ned|work=The Militant|date=18 March 1996|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the ''Helms-Burton Act'', the ''Foreign Extraterritorial Measures Act'' was amended to permit Canadians sued under the ''Helms-Burton Act'', to counter-sue in Canadian courts. The resulting amendment also found those that paid damages under the ''Helms-Burton Act'' to be liable to fines and imprisonment in Canada.<ref name=torst/> In a satirical response to the ''Helms-Burton Act'', a [[private member's bill]] known as the [[Godfrey-Milliken Bill]] was introduced in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in response to the extraterritoriality of the ''Helms-Burton Act''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.textfiles.com/politics/NWO/nwo_0012.txt |title=Bill C-339: The Godfrey-Milliken Bill |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618072721/http://web.textfiles.com/politics/NWO/nwo_0012.txt |archivedate=2013-06-18 |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/LegisInfo/BillDetails.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&billId=4771622|title=Private Member's Bill C-339|work=LEGISinfo|publisher=Parliament of Canada|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> The proposed bill would have allowed descendants of [[United Empire Loyalists]] who fled the [[American Revolution]] to be able to reclaim land and property that was confiscated by the American government in the 1700s. Although the ''Helms-Burton Act'' went into effect in 1996, enactment of Title III was postponed until April 2019.<ref name=torst/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.macleans.ca/article/1996/7/29/clintons-concession|title=Clinton's concession|work=Maclean's|publisher=Rogers Digital Media|first=Anthony|last=Wilson-Smith|date=29 July 1996|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/cuba/highlights-faits/2019/2019-04-18-helms-burton.aspx?lang=eng|title=Update on the Helms-Burton Act and Canadians doing business in Cuba|publisher=Government of Canada|website=Embassy of Canada to Cuba|date=18 April 2019|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the mid-1990s, Canada and Cuba reached an agreement that saw the Cuban government compensate Canadians whose properties were expropriated after the Cuban Revolution.<ref name=torst/> Emergency economic reforms made during the [[Special Period]] in Cuba, allowed for a significant number of Canadian businesses to invest in Cuba. Increased economic activity between the two countries prompted a 41-hour [[official visit]] to [[Havana]] by Canadian Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] in November 1998.<ref name=GaM>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/castro-and-trudeau-a-famous-but-also-fraught-friendship/article33058005/|title=Castro and Trudeau: a famous, but also fraught friendship|last=Robert|first=Wright|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|accessdate=25 July 2019|date=26 November 2016}}</ref> Chr\u00e9tien faced some criticism in Canada for not publicly voicing his concerns over [[human rights in Cuba]], although he privately discussed the issue with Castro, as well as demanded the release of four specific political dissidents.<ref name=chreitvisi>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/chretien-visits-cuba|title=Chr\u00e9tien visits Cuba|date=15 December 2013|accessdate=10 December 2019|publisher=Historica Canada|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia}}</ref> However, the visit saw no critique levied at Canada from the United States government; with U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] having urged Chr\u00e9tien at the [[24th G8 summit]] months earlier, to raise concerns about human rights to Castro during his planned visit.<ref name=chreitvisi/>\n\nCastro travelled to Montreal in 2000 to serve as one of Trudeau's pallbearers at [[State funeral of Pierre Trudeau|his funeral]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/americas/10/03/canada.castro.reut/index.html|website=CNN.com|publisher=Cable News Network|date=3 October 2000|title=Castro mourns for Trudeau, who stood up for him|accessdate=10 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120928052602/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/WORLD/americas/10/03/canada.castro.reut/index.html|archive-date=28 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\n====21st century====\nIn 2001, the Canadian government protested U.S. preclearance customs agents in Canadian airports who tried to catch American citizens travelling to Cuba in defiance of U.S. law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibike.org/cuba/ofac/010901-np.htm|first1=Glen|last1=McGregor|first2=Mike|last2=Trickey|title=Canada opposes U.S. crackdown on Cuba visitors|publisher=International Bicycle Fund|date=1 September 2001|accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> During the [[2010 United Nations Security Council election]], Cuban diplomats to the United Nations lobbied Latin American ambassadors to the [[United Nations General Assembly]] to vote for Canada.<ref name=macth>{{cite web|url=https://www.macleans.ca/politics/ottawa/canadas-cuban-ties-and-the-washington-havana-thaw/|title=Canada\u2019s Cuban ties and the Washington-Havana thaw|last=Geddes|first=John|date=18 December 2014|accessdate=17 August 2019|work=Maclean's|publisher=Rogers Digital Media}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Canadian government hosted bilateral talks between the governments of Cuba and the United States. Seven negotiation sessions were held between the American and Cuban governments in Ottawa and [[Toronto]].<ref name=macth/> The following negotiations led to the [[Cuban thaw|normalization of relations between the American and Cuban governments]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/facilitating-dialogue-canada-plays-host-to-secret-us-cuban-meetings/article22137559/|title=Facilitiating Dialogue: Canada plays host to secret U.S., Cuban meetings|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=25 July 2019|first=Campbell|last=Clark|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company}}</ref> In November 2016, Canadian Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]], made a 30-hour official visit to Cuba.<ref name=GaM/>\n\n==Economic relations==\nCuba is presently Canada's second largest export market in the Caribbean/[[Central American]] region, with over [[Canadian dollar|C$]]1 billion in goods traded annually.<ref name=CBC2>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/cuba-castro-succession-diaz-canel-canada-trudeau-1.4624529|title=Cuba's next president won't be a Castro. Here's what that means for Canada.|first=Mark|last=Kwong|work=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref> There are in total 85 Canadian companies and subsidiaries operating in Cuba, including brewer [[Labatt Breweries]]. \n\nApproximately 1.2 million Canadians visit Cuba annually.<ref name=CBC2/> With Canadian tourists account for 30 per cent of all tourists who visit Cuba per year, Canada is the largest source of tourists for Cuba.<ref name=\"cuba.gc.ca\"/>\n\n==Diplomatic representation==\n[[File:Embassy of Cuba in Canada (April 2005).jpg|thumb|The [[Embassy of Cuba, Ottawa|Cuban embassy]] in [[Ottawa]].]]\nCanada has had an embassy in Havana since 1945. The current building was built in 1929 and used by Canada since 1961. It also provides consular assistance to Australian and Israeli nationals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada-s-embassy-in-cuba-decrepit-says-audit-1.449604|title=Canada's embassy in Cuba decrepit, says audit|date=1 November 2009|accessdate=2 September 2017|work=CTV News|publisher=BellMedia}}</ref> The embassy is located in the upscale district of [[Miramar, Havana|Miramar]] in municipal area of Playa in Havana. Canadian consulates are also found in [[Varadero]] and [[Holguin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.gc.ca/assistance/embassies-consulates/cuba|title=Embassies and consulates: Cuba|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> due to these two locations being key destinations for Canadian tourists. \n\nCuba has an [[Embassy of Cuba, Ottawa|embassy in Ottawa]] and consulates in Montreal, and Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinMontreal.aspx|title=Consulate General of Cuba in Montreal|work=Embassy of Cuba in Canada|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Cuba|access-date=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414115649/http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinMontreal.aspx#|archive-date=14 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinToronto.aspx|title=Consulate General of Cuba in Toronto|work=Embassy of Cuba in Canada|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Cuba|access-date=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414110040/http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Mission/ConsulateGeneralinToronto.aspx#|archive-date=14 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Canada\u2013Caribbean relations]]\n*[[Canada\u2013Latin America relations]]\n*[[Cuban Canadian]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Canada]]\n*[[Foreign relations of Cuba]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/cuba/index.aspx?lang=eng Embassy of Canada in Havana]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130214012850/http://www.cubadiplomatica.cu/canada/EN/Home.aspx Embassy of Cuba in Canada]\n\n{{Foreign relations of Canada}}\n{{Foreign relations of Cuba}}\n{{Portal bar|Canada|Cuba|Politics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Canada-Cuba relations}}\n[[Category:Canada\u2013Cuba relations| ]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Canada|Cuba]]\n[[Category:Bilateral relations of Cuba]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typos for \"Encyclopedia\", replaced: Encylopedia \u2192 Encyclopedia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada%E2%80%93Cuba_relations"}
{"title_page": "Bible translations into Ge\u02bdez", "text_new": "[[File:Ethiopic genesis (ch. 29, v. 11-16), 15th century (The S.S. Teacher's Edition-The Holy Bible - Plate XII, 1).jpg|thumb|[[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] in Ge'ez]]\nThe '''Bible translations into [[Ge'ez]]''' date back to the 6th century at least, making them the one of the world's oldest Bible translations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scottishbiblesociety.org/2017/12/geez-new-testament-ethiopia-new-translation-one-worlds-oldest-scriptures/|title=A New Translation for one of the World's Oldest Scriptures|date=2017-12-08|website=Scottish Bible Society|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest translation of part of the Bible into Ge'ez are the [[Garima Gospels]].\n\n== History of the text ==\n{{See also|Orthodox Tewahedo biblical canon}}\nTranslations of the Bible in [[Ge'ez]], in a predecessor of the [[Ge\u02bdez script|Ge'ez script]] which did not possess vowels, were created between the 5th and 7th century,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> soon after the [[Christianity in Ethiopia#Christian Roots|Christianization of Ethiopia]] in the 4th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/acet/hd_acet.htm|title=African Christianity in Ethiopia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The milestones of the modern editions were the Roman \"Editio Princeps\" of the New Testament in 1548,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zuurmond|first=Rochus|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=nZIqKMRk6G0C&pg=PA464&lpg=PA464&dq=1548+aethiopice&source=bl&ots=Uv2U1kfgRR&sig=ACfU3U3RNEw0ZBEuCRcH_9sUFDE4hAWsxw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjS-9Df95_oAhUCjqQKHfFAAQwQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=1548%20aethiopice&f=false|title=Novum Testamentum Aethiopice: The Gospel of Matthew|date=2001|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|year=|isbn=978-3-447-04306-9|location=|pages=15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman|first=Bart D.|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=guYq9rohFQ8C&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=Testamentum+Novum+1548+tasfa&source=bl&ots=JHwFebIlxy&sig=ACfU3U2nPlgSZ_oxO2lLG-OZXtbmq2KGgw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwictayi-J_oAhWPPOwKHdbUC08Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Testamentum%20Novum%201548%20tasfa&f=false|title=The Text of the New Testament in Contemporary Research: Essays on the Status Quaestionis. Second Edition|last2=Holmes|first2=Michael W.|date=2012-11-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-23604-2|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref> and the critical edition of the New Testament by [[Thomas Pell Platt|Thomas P. Platt]] in 1830.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tau.ac.il/~hacohen/NT/Information.html|title=Information and Notes|website=www.tau.ac.il|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Translations ==\n\n=== Garima Gospels ===\n[[File:Illumination-from-Abba-Garima-gospel.jpg|right|thumb|320x320px|[[Evangelist portrait]] of [[Mark the Evangelist|Mark]] from Garima 2, likely the earlier of the two Garima Gospels]]\nThe [[Garima Gospels]] are the oldest translation of the Bible in Ge'ez and the world's earliest complete illustrated Christian manuscript.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|title=Ethiopian Bible is the oldest and complete bible on earth. \u00b7|last=|first=|date=31 August 2016|website=Ancient Origine|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901045246/http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|archive-date=2016-09-01|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> Monastic tradition holds that they were composed close to the year 500,<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jerome|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/unearthed-the-ancient-texts-that-tell-story-of-christianity-2019188.html|title=Unearthed, the ancient texts that tell story of Christianity|date=6 July 2010|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> a date supported by recent [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon analysis]]; samples from Garima 2 proposed a date of {{c.}} 390\u2013570, while counterpart dating of samples from Garima 1 proposed a date of {{c.}} 530\u2013660.<ref name=\"Bausi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|title=Ethiopia and the Mediterranean World in Late Antiquity: The Garim\u0101 Gospels in Context|last=Bausi|first=Alessandro|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Ethiopian Heritage Fund|page=2|format=Summary of conference proceedings|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503173517/http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|archivedate=3 May 2017|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Garima Gospels is also thought to be the oldest surviving Ge\u02bdez manuscript.<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite web|url=https://archaeologynewsnetwork.blogspot.com/2010/07/discovery-of-earliest-illuminated.html|title=\"Discovery of earliest illustrated manuscript,\" Martin Bailey, June 2010|author=A conservator at work on the Garima Gospels|first=|date=2010-07-14|website=|publisher=Theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|title=The Arts Newspaper June 2010 \u2013 Abuna Garima Gospels|publisher=Ethiopianheritagefund.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501030359/http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|archivedate=2012-05-01|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Later translations ===\nGe'ez Bible manuscripts exist until at least the late 17th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/collection-items/ethiopic-bible|title=Ethiopic Bible|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite journal|last=Mikre-Sellassie|first=G.A.|date=2000-07-01|title=The Early Translation of the Bible into Ethiopic/Geez|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/026009350005100302|journal=The Bible Translator|language=en|volume=51|issue=3|pages=302\u2013316|doi=10.1177/026009350005100302|issn=2051-6770}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://ethiopianorthodox.org/english/canonical/books.html Canon of the Ethiopian Othodox Church]\n* [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Alwan_Codex Alwan Codex]\n\n'''Editions'''\n\n*{{Cite book|last=|url=http://archive.org/details/novumtestamentu00platgoog|title=Novum Testamentum Domini Nostri et Servatoris Jesu Christi aethiopice|date=1830|publisher=Impressit R. Watts|others=University of Michigan|language=German|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|editor-last=Platt|editor-first=Thomas Pell}}\n*{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bub_gb_KPNa9Mc5gjYC|title=Testamentum Nouum cum epistola Pauli ad Hebreos tantum, cum concordantijs euangelistarum Eusebij & numeratione omnium verborum eorundem. Missale cum benedictione incensi cer\u00e6 ... Chaldea, qu\u00e6 omnia frater Petrus Ethyops ... imprimi curauit|date=1548|others=National Central Library of Rome|language=English}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bible Translations Into Geez}}\n[[Category:Apocrypha]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Bible versions and translations]]\n[[Category:Texts in Ge'ez]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ethiopic genesis (ch. 29, v. 11-16), 15th century (The S.S. Teacher's Edition-The Holy Bible - Plate XII, 1).jpg|thumb|[[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] in Ge'ez]]\nThe '''Bible translations into [[Ge'ez]]''' date back to the 6th century at least, making them the one of the world's oldest Bible translations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scottishbiblesociety.org/2017/12/geez-new-testament-ethiopia-new-translation-one-worlds-oldest-scriptures/|title=A New Translation for one of the World's Oldest Scriptures|date=2017-12-08|website=Scottish Bible Society|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest translation of part of the Bible into Ge'ez are the [[Garima Gospels]].\n\n== History of the text ==\n{{See also|Orthodox Tewahedo biblical canon}}\nTranslations of the Bible in [[Ge'ez]], in a predecessor of the [[Ge\u02bdez script|Ge'ez script]] which did not possess vowels, were created between the 5th and 7th century,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Geez-language|title=Ge\u02bfez language|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> soon after the [[Christianity in Ethiopia#Christian Roots|Christianization of Ethiopia]] in the 4th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/acet/hd_acet.htm|title=African Christianity in Ethiopia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.metmuseum.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The milestones of the modern editions were the Roman \"Editio Princeps\" of the New Testament in 1548,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zuurmond|first=Rochus|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=nZIqKMRk6G0C&pg=PA464&lpg=PA464&dq=1548+aethiopice&source=bl&ots=Uv2U1kfgRR&sig=ACfU3U3RNEw0ZBEuCRcH_9sUFDE4hAWsxw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjS-9Df95_oAhUCjqQKHfFAAQwQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=1548%20aethiopice&f=false|title=Novum Testamentum Aethiopice: The Gospel of Matthew|date=2001|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|year=|isbn=978-3-447-04306-9|location=|pages=15|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman|first=Bart D.|url=https://books.google.be/books?id=guYq9rohFQ8C&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=Testamentum+Novum+1548+tasfa&source=bl&ots=JHwFebIlxy&sig=ACfU3U2nPlgSZ_oxO2lLG-OZXtbmq2KGgw&hl=fr&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwictayi-J_oAhWPPOwKHdbUC08Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Testamentum%20Novum%201548%20tasfa&f=false|title=The Text of the New Testament in Contemporary Research: Essays on the Status Quaestionis. Second Edition|last2=Holmes|first2=Michael W.|date=2012-11-09|publisher=BRILL|year=|isbn=978-90-04-23604-2|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref> and the critical edition of the New Testament by [[Thomas Pell Platt|Thomas P. Platt]] in 1830.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tau.ac.il/~hacohen/NT/Information.html|title=Information and Notes|website=www.tau.ac.il|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Translations ==\n\n=== Garima Gospels ===\n[[File:Illumination-from-Abba-Garima-gospel.jpg|right|thumb|320x320px|[[Evangelist portrait]] of [[Mark the Evangelist|Mark]] from Garima 2, likely the earlier of the two Garima Gospels]]\nThe [[Garima Gospels]] are the oldest translation of the Bible in Ge'ez. It is the world's earliest complete illustrated Christian manuscript.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|title=Ethiopian Bible is the oldest and complete bible on earth. \u00b7|last=|first=|date=31 August 2016|website=Ancient Origine|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901045246/http://www.ancient-origine.com/ethiopian-bible-oldest-complete-bible-earth/|archive-date=2016-09-01|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> Monastic tradition holds that they were composed close to the year 500,<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite news|last=Taylor|first=Jerome|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/unearthed-the-ancient-texts-that-tell-story-of-christianity-2019188.html|title=Unearthed, the ancient texts that tell story of Christianity|date=6 July 2010|work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> a date supported by recent [[Radiocarbon dating|radiocarbon analysis]]; samples from Garima 2 proposed a date of {{c.}} 390\u2013570, while counterpart dating of samples from Garima 1 proposed a date of {{c.}} 530\u2013660.<ref name=\"Bausi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|title=Ethiopia and the Mediterranean World in Late Antiquity: The Garim\u0101 Gospels in Context|last=Bausi|first=Alessandro|date=5 November 2013|publisher=Ethiopian Heritage Fund|page=2|format=Summary of conference proceedings|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503173517/http://www.ethiopianheritagefund.org/document-page-2|archivedate=3 May 2017|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Garima Gospels is also thought to be the oldest surviving Ge\u02bdez manuscript.<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite web|url=https://archaeologynewsnetwork.blogspot.com/2010/07/discovery-of-earliest-illuminated.html|title=\"Discovery of earliest illustrated manuscript,\" Martin Bailey, June 2010|author=A conservator at work on the Garima Gospels|first=|date=2010-07-14|website=|publisher=Theartnewspaper.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|title=The Arts Newspaper June 2010 \u2013 Abuna Garima Gospels|publisher=Ethiopianheritagefund.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501030359/http://ethiopianheritagefund.org/artsNewspaper.html|archivedate=2012-05-01|accessdate=2012-07-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Later translations ===\nGe'ez Bible manuscripts exist until at least the late 17th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/collection-items/ethiopic-bible|title=Ethiopic Bible|website=The British Library|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the [[Ethiopian Catholic Church]] and the [[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] associated themselves with the Bible Society of Ethiopia to produce a printed version of the Bible in Ge'ez. The [[New Testament]] was released in 2017.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite journal|last=Mikre-Sellassie|first=G.A.|date=2000-07-01|title=The Early Translation of the Bible into Ethiopic/Geez|url=https://doi.org/10.1177/026009350005100302|journal=The Bible Translator|language=en|volume=51|issue=3|pages=302\u2013316|doi=10.1177/026009350005100302|issn=2051-6770}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://ethiopianorthodox.org/english/canonical/books.html Canon of the Ethiopian Othodox Church]\n* [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Alwan_Codex Alwan Codex]\n\n'''Editions'''\n\n*{{Cite book|last=|url=http://archive.org/details/novumtestamentu00platgoog|title=Novum Testamentum Domini Nostri et Servatoris Jesu Christi aethiopice|date=1830|publisher=Impressit R. Watts|others=University of Michigan|language=German|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|editor-last=Platt|editor-first=Thomas Pell}}\n*{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bub_gb_KPNa9Mc5gjYC|title=Testamentum Nouum cum epistola Pauli ad Hebreos tantum, cum concordantijs euangelistarum Eusebij & numeratione omnium verborum eorundem. Missale cum benedictione incensi cer\u00e6 ... Chaldea, qu\u00e6 omnia frater Petrus Ethyops ... imprimi curauit|date=1548|others=National Central Library of Rome|language=English}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bible Translations Into Geez}}\n[[Category:Apocrypha]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Bible versions and translations]]\n[[Category:Texts i